You might not see it at first - it is a quiet area behind shops, not where you expect to find homes. But if you go behind the old, closed Whole Foods store and walk behind the hotels that are only open for family reunions, you will find a complete community. Many apartment buildings are there, all placed carefully like Russian nesting dolls. The first buildings you see are not good - they were on the news for bad things. But the others are different. Across the road is a college's small campus. Students go there early in the morning. The road meets another road with a park. There is a treatment center for people who have broken bones. Children play and old people walk their dogs. There is a sushi place, a pool supply store, a salon, and a frozen yogurt shop. This part of town is like a slice of American history - not much changes there.

"Where is everything?" she asked. We drove past the corn fields. "Here it is!" I said. She was from a city. She had never seen so much open space. I told her what it was like growing up in rural Ohio. She understood now who I was and where I came from. We drove on a two-lane road. There was a quarry with water. Past it was a small development. The houses were brick and stucco. Each house had half an acre of land. Everyone took care of their lawn. In spring, there were flowers and trees. The driveways had Mercedes cars. My neighbor was always outside. He was a doctor. He mowed his lawn and sang. Everyone liked him. He was older and lost some humor. I live in a grey house. There are geese in the side yard. Our dog chases them. Out back, there is a stream. You can hear bullfrogs. There are cows nearby. Across a wooden bridge is an untouched oasis. I spent my childhood here. I built tree forts and hunted animals. In winter, the trees lose their leaves. Everything turns white with snow. My sister and I fought. We made snowballs and forts. We played pretend. It was like a wonderland.

Portland has a special feeling. The city is known for being "weird". This is shown on a building that is many things: a pizza place, bar, music venue, and strip club. It also does not follow all the rules. Old Portland is remembered by the slogan "Keep Portland Weird". People come to Portland because they want to be weird, and this is accepted here. Even with new people and buildings, Portland stays weird. It has many normal things too, like yoga, hipsters, and business people. Weird does not mean no rules, but it does mean being open to different things. Weird Portland has colorful houses and free boxes. These boxes have clothes, books, or other things. People like to find these things. Portland has problems too. There are drug and homelessness issues. The city has many people who dream and work hard. Portland is full of good and bad. This makes it special and different.

The mountains are always there. Every morning and evening, they watch the sun rise and set. Sometimes I forget about them, or life gets busy. But they are always there, strong and steady, no matter what happens. When I am very tired or stressed, I see them and feel better. They give me strength to go on. I first saw them when I moved here for college. The mountains are special to me. They are more important than the university buildings and trees. The town has many good places. There are many cafes where students study. Downtown has old, colored buildings. It is busy and active, like a big city. Then, near the library, it is quiet and peaceful. This mix of feelings makes the town interesting. I have many happy memories here. I walk to the park with friends, or run downtown to see a movie. There are also sad memories. The ponds are a good place to think or cry. I have cried there many times. I think about life and my purpose. I walk past the pond and the park, and then I reach a main street. The sun shines on the palm trees and makes the sky beautiful. I look at the mountains and feel strong. They are always there, watching me.

If you are planning to visit Bensonhurt, Brooklyn, you will have no problem finding it. Public transportation is easy and used by many people in New York City. Bensonhurt is a busy neighborhood, so you will still feel like you are in New York City. During your visit, you will see many Asian stores. In the past 20 years, many Asian people have moved to Bensonhurt. You will see many Asian-owned stores, often supermarkets and laundromats. These stores are popular with local residents because the food is good, the prices are low, and they are convenient. Near my home, there are four Asian supermarkets within two minutes of walking distance. The neighborhood is not only Asian. There are many immigrants and their children there. Most big and popular stores are owned by Asians. Also, there is a new park with many sports courts, swings, and a water fountain for kids. This park is very popular. The neighborhood has many two-family homes. Most people are nice, but it can be noisy. Every day, you will hear cars playing loud music and people speeding. If you visit at night, be careful. The neighborhood is safe, but people can be unpredictable. Be ready for bullies and thieves. I have been bullied and had my packages stolen in the past. Also, people do not pick up dog waste. Everyday, you will see dog waste on streets. Be careful and keep your shoes clean!

I live near the top of a very steep hill. There are not many sidewalks. People call it "work out hill" because many joggers run up it. There are many potholes on the road. Trees grow everywhere, but people want to cut them down. They block the view of the ocean. The houses are tall with big glass windows. In the evenings, the water is bright. It is often cloudy and damp. Moss grows on many things. Many dogs live here. Some are big and can get into houses. Rabbits are also common. Cats love to catch them. There are few birds. There are no stores. But there are restaurants near the water. The bay is not wide. I can see the other side. It is nice to throw stones into the water.

I live in a typical suburb area in a small southern town in Tennessee. It is a street between two state highways, so we get more traffic than I'd like. But, otherwise, it's a quiet neighborhood. Not many people move in or out, so I know most of the neighbors. They busy themselves with yard work and other daily chores. In the winter, we sled down the hill on our side street. We live at the front corner of our street, so we see everyone coming and going. We pay attention to strange vehicles. Some neighbors walk for exercise or to walk their dogs. Kids play on their bikes. We are home a lot because we work from home. There are four of us: myself, my wife, and two daughters, ages eleven and fourteen. Other neighbors know that we come and go often. We play outside, sometimes even in the rain. Sometimes we grill outside on our back deck. It smells good. Many neighbors cut grass from March through October. There are many trees, so there are leaves in the fall. We rake and burn leaves yearly. I like the smell of burning leaves. Recently, we haven't had much winter, so it feels like a long fall. Our garage is at the back of our house, so we seldom use the front door. I like working in the garage on my truck or other projects. When the garage doors are open, I feel more connected to the neighborhood. On holidays, it is quiet. Thanksgiving sees neighbors visiting with relatives from out of town. There are extra cars parked everywhere. The same happens at other holidays like Mother's Day and Christmas. Overall, I like living here. If it weren't a through street, it would be perfect.

My neighborhood is in the middle of the desert. The ground is all dirt. If you don't live here, you can't understand how it feels to see brown everywhere. If you see a lawn, it's because the owner spends a lot of money on it. When I first moved here in the 90s, houses were far apart. Now it's the same, but there are many new buildings. It's like a city, which is changing everywhere. People are usually friendly, but like any city, there are good and bad areas. In my neighborhood, I have friendly old people around. The stores here have chains like Food 4 Less and Smart & Final. If you want organic food, you have to travel. Most jobs in my city are in construction because they are still building. I don't want my city to change too much. I came from a big city and don't want to return. My job is installing drywall and T-bar. I like the animals here. Many people come for the desert's beauty. My children love lizards and desert bugs. There are some attractions here. If you visit in September, you can go to the annual San Bernardino County Fair. You can also go to Wrightwood to see snow-covered mountains. The Victor Valley Museum tells the history of the desert and its people.

My neighborhood is different. I live on a college campus, and my community is my dorm. The campus also counts as my neighborhood. Like other neighborhoods, it has houses, people, stores, and a park.

First, let's talk about the houses. There are three types. Apartment buildings have 2-4 people per room, 4-6 rooms per floor, and 20 people per building. There are also houses for school alumni, but fewer of these. Dorm rooms are the most common; they house 2 students each with some exceptions.

My school is diverse. People live in houses, apartments, or dorms. Young students live in dorms. Older students live in apartments. Staff lives in houses.

The neighborhood has stores and a park. Stores offer food and clothes. The park is clean and safe for everyone.

I have lived here for 10 years. I was sad when I moved from Riverdale to Stockbridge. I missed my old neighborhood. But my parents wanted a better life for my sister and me. Our new neighborhood was not considered “ghetto”. I made new friends and some enemies at school. I knew my neighbors Mr. Glen, Ms. Veda, and Dennis. They were like family to me. I went to Mr. Glen’s wedding and danced with his daughter Marsharii. I haven’t seen her since. I enjoy exploring my neighborhood with GPS. I hang out with friends at the park. I bring a bokken to practice balance. There is a basketball and tennis court, but I haven’t played there in a long time. My father taught me tennis with Mr. Graves. These are my favorite memories. I believe the best is yet to come!

My home is near to the college where I study, which I enjoy. There are many apartment buildings and a few restaurants and bars. One bar is more expensive but not bad. Most people are nice. There are many children because there is an elementary school nearby. I don’t know my neighbors, and they smoke a lot of weed. The management put an air freshener near their door. The buildings are old but some have been renovated. Nearby, there are new apartments, but they are cheaply built and expensive to rent. There is a cheap restaurant nearby that serves food on paper plates. A gas station is across the street, which is not a good place to work. The road was improved last year with money from the city. There are many trees around my apartment building, but some were cut down. Behind my building are more trees and another apartment complex. I live on 42nd Street, but 43rd Street behind is not as nice. The sidewalks are bad, and many buildings look shabby. Some crime happens at an apartment complex on 43rd Street. I like where I live because I can afford it and there are useful amenities nearby. The university is within walking distance and there are two bus stops for going to the store and downtown.

I live in a neighborhood with duplex houses on a cul-de-sac. They are separated and painted yellow with white porches and green roofs. Most people are friends. We stand and chat in the evening while children play. It is peaceful, like stepping back in time. We are near fields and trees with blue skies and white clouds. Recently, we had a tornado warning. Last night, we heard sirens. I was in the bathtub with my small dog, purse, and pillows. My big dog was scared and barked in the living room. After the storm, the road was hot and steaming. Hail melted quickly. Then, it rained and a rainbow appeared. I took pictures and shared them. Later, people came home. It was quiet and peaceful. I live in a two-bedroom, two-bathroom apartment. Most houses look the same outside, but inside are different sizes. I love to walk to a big field and see deer. In the morning, I hear bullfrogs and roosters. It is like living in a small village. A donkey at a nearby farm makes sounds at night. I am happy to live here, 40 minutes from Charlotte.

I moved to this neighborhood when I was about to start eighth grade. It was hard to make friends at first, but I became close with someone who lives two houses away and another boy who lived on my street. They do not live here anymore, but I still remember them. Most people who lived here when I moved are still here. My neighborhood is like a typical American suburban area. It has many two-story houses. On weekends, I hear kids playing outside. Most days are quiet. I have never had problems with neighbors. I feel safe. The park a few minutes from my house has many memories. I played basketball, football, and baseball there. I have bad memories too, like getting hit in the nose playing football. But good memories are better. Now, I go there to play with my cousin's kids. They are younger and love swings and slides. The park makes me feel nostalgic. The neighborhood is diverse. There are Chinese, Indian, Mexican, and Italian restaurants nearby. Most people order food online now. There are many stores. I have a Walgreens and a CVS near my house. There is also an Indian-owned store. I like my neighborhood. I am grateful for it. I see bad things happen to other neighborhoods on news and social media.

Our town is quiet. It is not special, but it is important for farming. Johnston is the Peach Capital of the World. Many people grow peaches or raise cattle. The houses are far apart, with metal or gray shingles. Most people live near their fields. The main street has only one stop light and a few stores. There are three fast food places. There is a small pharmacy and one grocery store. Many people buy groceries at Walmart in Batesburg-Leesville. The best store is Dollar General. There is a small furniture store and a pet grooming place. The town has one school. Doctor and vet offices are near. There are no parks, but a new recreational area is coming. There is not much to do, but it is a nice town.

I first heard about my neighborhood when I listened to a podcast about missing people. It was a surprise. Most apartments in the area cost over a thousand dollars a month. I didn't know this, and neither did my friends. Maybe it's because we are struggling. Many of my friends cry at night. Things are expensive, but we know how to save money. You get used to the smell of old things. The flea market is always there. You can find three thrift stores nearby. If you start on the far side, you can visit two charity thrifts, a library, a rare book store, and a curio shop. Downtown is busy with cars and people every morning, but the stores are quiet. It's a good place to spend an afternoon. Every year, more people come. The city is growing. There's an online business here, but it still has problems. It reminds me of New York. Everyone is busy, and no one asks for help. You can be alone if you want. You don't need to share your life. It's different from the South, where everyone cares a lot. No one here asks about others' lives. You can be quiet as long as you want. The city is lively. There's always something happening. A pianist lives next door, and two singers live upstairs. My neighbors are like friends. We help each other. I like most of them. I try to be clean and leave food for them. They do the same for me. We bring mail to each other. I feel lucky to live here. I like most of my neighbors. I live in a big, modern city, but it's my neighbors who make me feel good.

I live in a typical cookie cutter suburb. The neighborhood is well-maintained. The homeowner's association makes sure of this. All homes are single-family. They have small yards with grass, pebbles, and short driveways. Most homes have two-car garages. The roads are new and smooth. There are no potholes. Most houses are one story, but some are two stories. Mailboxes are at the end of the street. Everyone uses a key to get to their box.

The neighborhood is near the city, but it is also rural. There is plenty of land. There are large community pools and walking trails. Most people here are retired. They look out for each other. There are also some middle-aged and young professionals. The city is big, but it has a small-town feel. We have most things we need. There is one mall. It has high-end grocery stores and bargain outlets. My neighborhood is safe and well-maintained. I can exercise without going to a park. I can drive a short time to major stores.

I live in a small town near a big city. My home is in a poor area of the town. Many people here are poor. They live in old houses. Most people are friendly. They smile and say hello when I walk by. Crime is a little higher here. There have been some shootings and one murder nearby. Some people have lost family members to shootings. My family has not been hurt. Many people in town use drugs. They die from drug overdoses. Fentanyl is very bad. My town has centers to help people with drug problems. My son's school is very good. Teachers and staff are kind. My son has special needs, but he is happy. The Parent-Teacher Organization plans events. They help families and schools. The school provides free breakfast and lunch. No child is poor. Some children have special needs. The town looks better now. Roads, parks, and stores are fixed. But the east side is not fixed. People here do not like this. My family has lived here for 16 years. We like it here.

My neighborhood is full of culture. It is on a hill, with buildings that have history. I live in a 7-story apartment building near the old live theater. Nearby, there is a small bar that many people visit. It is a popular place, especially during summer nights. A few blocks up is a big city park. It has concrete walls with stairs. In winter, homeless people set up tents in the park. It rains a lot, and it can be difficult to stay warm. They are close to a family center where they can bathe and shower. I love my neighborhood because of the people. In the past, Hilltop was known for gang violence. The government tried to stop this. People remember this. They work hard to keep the neighborhood clean. They care about what happens in their city. They say people should not walk around Hilltop at night if they are white. This advice is from the past, and it is because of social conditioning. I believe this warning is from the old days. It is because of racism and fear. I feel alive in Hilltop at night. People have helped me in many ways. One time, I was in the rain and needed to charge my phone. A laundromat owner stayed open for me. I have sat in the rain and felt invisible. But someone stopped and gave me $5. They told me I was beautiful and valuable. I know Hilltop is my home.

I live in Rural America, specifically a small town in Michigan. We go from farmland to small tourist cities. There are no big city stores, like Wal-Mart or Target. We have to drive for anything. But I live in a beautiful place. Lake Michigan and Lake Charlevoix surround my town. Everywhere has a beach to swim. My neighborhood shows small-town life. Houses are not big and same. They are older, with basements. Most have aluminum siding. Colors vary. Many have trampolines, gardens, fences for animals. People are hard workers. They like safety and peace. Neighbors know each other. They wave, smile, keep yards clean. Most houses are average, but safe and peaceful. Nearby are the sheriff's department, health department, recycling center, baseball fields, small airport, ice cream shop, and a park. I like living here. It is good for families.
